Project 4: QR Code Phishing (Quishing) Awareness Simulation

Objective
-----------
The objective of this project was to research and simulate QR-code based phishing attacks (quishing) and understand the risks associated with malicious QR redirection and credential theft.

Project Description
--------------------

This project focused on studying the emerging threat of QR phishing (Quishing) by generating QR codes that redirected users to cloned phishing pages within a controlled lab environment. The goal was to understand how attackers may abuse trust in QR interactions to steal credentials.

I created simulated QR redirection scenarios where a scanned QR code led to a fake login portal designed for awareness testing. This demonstrated how users may unknowingly trust QR codes and submit sensitive information to malicious sites.

The project also explored why mobile phishing introduces additional challenges, such as limited URL visibility, reduced verification behavior, and increased trust in quick interactions.

In addition to attack simulation, I studied defensive measures such as QR verification awareness, safe mobile browsing practices, multi-factor authentication protection, and user awareness campaigns aimed at reducing quishing risks.

This project helped me understand a growing phishing vector and how emerging threats can be analyzed from both attacker and defender perspectives.

